845
00:55:35,766 --> 00:55:37,099
Depose you.

846
00:55:38,369 --> 00:55:39,368
Shall we?

847
00:55:39,370 --> 00:55:40,869
Yeah.

848
00:55:43,808 --> 00:55:44,807
He had a gold leaf on them.

849
00:55:44,809 --> 00:55:45,808
I know.

850
00:55:46,811 --> 00:55:47,810
Come!

851
00:55:47,812 --> 00:55:48,977
Judge Hallow?

852
00:55:48,979 --> 00:55:49,978
Yes?

853
00:55:49,980 --> 00:55:50,979
Stu Pepper, Your Honor.

854
00:55:50,981 --> 00:55:51,980
The lawyer in the Thacker case.

855
00:55:51,982 --> 00:55:54,116
Oh.

856
00:55:54,118 --> 00:55:55,851
Greg.

857
00:55:55,853 --> 00:55:57,453
You're here on Officer Dodge's
motion for summary judgment.

858
00:55:57,455 --> 00:55:58,954
I am.

859
00:55:58,956 --> 00:56:01,590
Fifteen counts, Mr. Pepper.
Very ambitious.

860
00:56:01,592 --> 00:56:03,058
It is.

861
00:56:03,060 --> 00:56:05,861
Your Honor, I move
for dismissal of all counts.

862
00:56:07,431 --> 00:56:09,031
I'm throwing out
14 of the counts.

863
00:56:09,033 --> 00:56:10,532
Why?

864
00:56:10,534 --> 00:56:13,435
Insufficient evidence.

865
00:56:13,437 --> 00:56:14,570
It's all circumstantial.

866
00:56:14,572 --> 00:56:16,532
Didn't you learn that
in law school?

867
00:56:18,376 --> 00:56:21,443
You're throwing out
14 out of 15 counts?

868
00:56:21,445 --> 00:56:23,679
Okay.
What count are you keeping?

869
00:56:23,681 --> 00:56:26,115
"Excessive force." Barely.

870
00:56:26,117 --> 00:56:27,950
Your Honor, can I be frank?

871
00:56:27,952 --> 00:56:29,418
If you must.

872
00:56:29,420 --> 00:56:31,487
You used to be
city attorney, correct?

873
00:56:31,489 --> 00:56:34,523
You used to be him:
Defending these guys.

874
00:56:34,525 --> 00:56:38,427
Is there any chance this could
be a conflict of interest?

875
00:56:43,701 --> 00:56:45,667
Are you hinting I may not be

876
00:56:45,669 --> 00:56:47,636
fair and impartial, Mr. Pepper?

877
00:56:49,440 --> 00:56:51,573
You've got a case to prepare,

878
00:56:51,575 --> 00:56:53,792
and people to answer to.

879
00:56:53,793 --> 00:56:56,010
Exactly how smart is it to piss
off the judge before the trial?

880
00:56:56,013 --> 00:56:59,081
I'm not trying to piss you off.

881
00:56:59,083 --> 00:57:02,117
And I'll take your one count
of excessive force,

882
00:57:02,119 --> 00:57:04,953
because that's all I need
to win the case.

883
00:57:04,955 --> 00:57:07,589
Thank you, gentlemen.
I will see you both in court.

884
00:57:12,663 --> 00:57:14,863
But don't worry
about it getting dirty.

885
00:57:14,865 --> 00:57:17,132
I have to take things to the
cleaners every once in awhile.

886
00:57:17,134 --> 00:57:19,201
I like your scarf too.

887
00:57:26,677 --> 00:57:28,477
Why aren't you sleeping?

888
00:57:31,715 --> 00:57:33,782
I don't know.

889
00:57:37,555 --> 00:57:41,623
Nance, um,
I'm not sure what to do.

890
00:57:45,830 --> 00:57:49,665
I got an FBI director
that could care less,

891
00:57:49,667 --> 00:57:52,868
got a judge that throws out
95% of my counts.

892
00:57:52,870 --> 00:57:57,172
Same judge who used to make
his living defending cops.

893
00:57:58,809 --> 00:58:01,710
Baby, I'm so sorry.

894
00:58:05,850 --> 00:58:08,951
I just want you to be careful.

895
00:58:08,953 --> 00:58:13,055
Think about what it means
to prosecute cop after cop.

896
00:58:13,057 --> 00:58:16,925
Stu, these people
can make our lives miserable.

897
00:58:16,927 --> 00:58:21,196
Yeah, but they're already
making peoples' lives miserable.

898
00:58:23,801 --> 00:58:26,168
Somebody's gotta take a stand.

899
00:58:28,239 --> 00:58:30,119
You don't have to
do it tonight.

900
00:58:33,143 --> 00:58:35,244
Come on, let's go to bed.

901
00:58:44,855 --> 00:58:46,288
<i>All right, break it up.</i>

902
00:58:46,290 --> 00:58:47,956
<i>Break it up, I said.</i>

903
00:59:17,721 --> 00:59:21,857
<i>An honest man</i>
<i>is always a child.</i>

904
00:59:21,859 --> 00:59:24,026
<i>But it's even simpler.</i>

905
00:59:24,028 --> 00:59:27,095
<i>What has been lost</i>
<i>and what has been gained?</i>

906
00:59:28,098 --> 00:59:30,198
<i>I was close to the Thackers,</i>

907
00:59:30,200 --> 00:59:34,836
<i>seeing my own image</i>
<i>in their loss.</i>

908
00:59:34,838 --> 00:59:37,139
<i>I never knew if I was</i>
<i>their last stop on a long list</i>

909
00:59:37,141 --> 00:59:40,275
<i>that I just happened to be</i>
<i>at the bottom of.</i>

910
00:59:40,277 --> 00:59:43,712
<i>I was learning that</i>
<i>the self-doubt, the anxiety,</i>

911
00:59:43,714 --> 00:59:46,682
<i>sleepless nights,</i>
<i>time away from my own family</i>

912
00:59:46,684 --> 00:59:51,587
<i>was to be expected</i>
<i>if I was going to succeed.</i>

913
00:59:51,589 --> 00:59:53,255
<i>I had become close</i>
<i>to a young man</i>

914
00:59:53,257 --> 00:59:56,158
<i>who I have never had</i>
<i>the opportunity to meet.</i>

915
00:59:56,160 --> 00:59:58,660
<i>His justice</i>
<i>rests on my shoulders.</i>

916
01:00:01,665 --> 01:00:05,867
<i>I can't raise the dead,</i>
<i>but I have to speak for them.</i>

917
01:00:30,861 --> 01:00:34,329
Jury members,
you are being asked to decide

918
01:00:34,331 --> 01:00:36,965
whether excessive force
was used

919
01:00:36,967 --> 01:00:39,368
during the arrest
of Kevin Thacker.

920
01:00:39,370 --> 01:00:41,370
The city attorneys
will attempt to prove

921
01:00:41,372 --> 01:00:44,740
that Mr. Thacker escaped custody
during his booking,

922
01:00:44,742 --> 01:00:48,810
and died accidentally
during this getaway.

923
01:00:50,014 --> 01:00:51,947
The attorneys for the Thackers
will attempt to prove

924
01:00:51,949 --> 01:00:53,682
that the head trauma
he incurred

925
01:00:53,684 --> 01:00:57,252
could not have happened
the way it was reported.

926
01:00:57,254 --> 01:01:01,423
It is your charge to determine
what you believe the truth is.

927
01:01:26,183 --> 01:01:29,418
Mr. Pepper, please call
your first witness.

928
01:01:29,420 --> 01:01:32,888
Your Honor, I would like
to call Officer John Dodge.

929
01:01:35,893 --> 01:01:38,160
Officer Dodge,

930
01:01:38,162 --> 01:01:41,430
let me start out by asking
a very simple question.

931
01:01:44,401 --> 01:01:47,369
Go ahead.

932
01:01:47,371 --> 01:01:49,004
Do you normally
brush your teeth

933
01:01:49,006 --> 01:01:50,966
before you go to work
in the morning?

934
01:01:51,408 --> 01:01:52,874
Yes.

935
01:01:55,412 --> 01:01:57,292
And have you ever
killed anyone?

936
01:02:01,018 --> 01:02:02,284
Yes, I have.

937
01:02:02,286 --> 01:02:05,887
I was in
the 25th Infantry division

938
01:02:05,889 --> 01:02:09,191
at Cu Chi and Dau Tieng,
Vietnam.

939
01:02:09,193 --> 01:02:12,260
And in what manner

940
01:02:12,262 --> 01:02:15,363
did you perform
these killings in Vietnam?

941
01:02:16,467 --> 01:02:20,168
With my rifle.
Sometimes my bayonet.

942
01:02:20,170 --> 01:02:22,204
All in self-defense.

943
01:02:25,075 --> 01:02:27,943
Just to be clear for the Jury.

944
01:02:27,945 --> 01:02:29,111
Self-defense?

945
01:02:29,113 --> 01:02:31,012
I learned to make
quick decisions

946
01:02:31,014 --> 01:02:32,280
in delicate situations.

947
01:02:32,282 --> 01:02:34,382
I guess that's why
I became a cop.

948
01:02:34,384 --> 01:02:37,819
Quick decisions
in delicate situations.

949
01:02:37,821 --> 01:02:39,888
Hmm.

950
01:02:39,890 --> 01:02:41,022
What's your height and weight?

951
01:02:41,024 --> 01:02:43,925
6'1", 210 pounds.

952
01:02:43,927 --> 01:02:48,764
And Kevin Thacker was 5'7",
133 pounds.

953
01:02:48,766 --> 01:02:52,000
That's quite a difference,
isn't it?

954
01:02:52,002 --> 01:02:54,402
Well, I'm bigger
than most people,

955
01:02:54,404 --> 01:02:56,538
so it's no surprise to me.

956
01:02:56,540 --> 01:03:00,275
On the night
of October 29th, 1983,

957
01:03:00,277 --> 01:03:02,878
did a struggle occur
in the alleyway

958
01:03:02,880 --> 01:03:04,479
behind the Marshalltown
Police Department,

959
01:03:04,481 --> 01:03:06,281
between yourself
and Kevin Thacker?

960
01:03:06,283 --> 01:03:07,549
No, it did not.

961
01:03:07,551 --> 01:03:09,050
And during that struggle,

962
01:03:09,052 --> 01:03:11,887
being a man
of your size and experience,

963
01:03:11,889 --> 01:03:14,222
you struck Kevin on the left
side of the head killing him.

964
01:03:14,224 --> 01:03:16,258
Is that correct?

965
01:03:16,260 --> 01:03:18,460
No, I did not.

966
01:03:18,462 --> 01:03:20,663
I was simply trying to find
an escaped prisoner.

967
01:03:29,206 --> 01:03:31,373
Prisoner is loose
in the building.

968
01:03:44,488 --> 01:03:46,555
Shit.

969
01:03:59,236 --> 01:04:00,936
Shit.

970
01:04:03,540 --> 01:04:05,307
Call an ambulance.

971
01:04:14,518 --> 01:04:18,286
From the time that Kevin
asked to use the bathroom,

972
01:04:18,288 --> 01:04:21,289
to the time that
you found him unconscious,

973
01:04:21,291 --> 01:04:25,460
that was approximately
seven minutes, correct?

974
01:04:25,462 --> 01:04:27,195
Yes, that's right.

975
01:04:27,196 --> 01:04:28,929
He was in the bathroom
for just under two minutes,

976
01:04:28,932 --> 01:04:31,032
and we were walking out.

977
01:04:31,034 --> 01:04:33,568
I went to turn
the video camera back on,

978
01:04:33,570 --> 01:04:36,538
and then I realized
that he had fled.

979
01:04:36,540 --> 01:04:38,774
After a search,

980
01:04:38,775 --> 01:04:41,009
I came back a minute later
to turn the camera off,

981
01:04:41,011 --> 01:04:45,180
and with the assistance of other
officers, did another search.

982
01:04:45,182 --> 01:04:47,916
Well, why bother
to come all the way back

983
01:04:47,918 --> 01:04:49,451
to turn the video camera off?

984
01:04:49,453 --> 01:04:51,119
There was nobody
was in the room.

985
01:04:51,121 --> 01:04:52,654
It was an instinct.

986
01:04:52,655 --> 01:04:54,188
And we all have
certain instincts

987
01:04:54,191 --> 01:04:57,225
that force us
to do certain things, correct?

988
01:04:57,227 --> 01:04:59,961
Kevin Thacker
would still be alive today

989
01:04:59,963 --> 01:05:03,064
if he would have just
allowed me to do my job.

990
01:05:03,066 --> 01:05:06,501
Kevin had to allow you
to do your job?

991
01:05:09,606 --> 01:05:11,973
I don't think it's that simple,
Officer Dodge.

992
01:05:14,211 --> 01:05:16,091
No further questions,
Your Honor.

993
01:05:26,924 --> 01:05:29,491
Professor Daily,
can you tell the court

994
01:05:29,493 --> 01:05:32,627
what a standing broad jump is?

995
01:05:32,629 --> 01:05:34,562
A standing broad jump
is an event

996
01:05:34,564 --> 01:05:37,232
in which the competitor
stands at a line,

997
01:05:37,234 --> 01:05:40,068
and from a standing posture,
they jump as far as they can.

998
01:05:40,070 --> 01:05:42,237
And what's the world's record
for such a jump?

999
01:05:42,239 --> 01:05:45,173
The longest jump
is 12 feet, one inch.

1000
01:05:45,175 --> 01:05:49,177
And do you think anyone,
even a trained athlete,

1001
01:05:49,179 --> 01:05:52,080
could make such a jump?

1002
01:05:52,082 --> 01:05:53,315
No.

1003
01:05:53,317 --> 01:05:56,151
Have you done any tests
to verify this?

1004
01:05:56,153 --> 01:05:58,119
Yes, I did.

1005
01:05:58,121 --> 01:06:00,522
Several of my swimmers
jumped from a platform

1006
01:06:00,524 --> 01:06:04,159
similar to the one Kevin Thacker
allegedly leaped from.

1007
01:06:04,161 --> 01:06:06,494
Right. What were the results?

1008
01:06:06,496 --> 01:06:09,698
None of them were able
to complete the 12 feet.

1009
01:06:09,700 --> 01:06:12,600
Not even close.

1010
01:06:12,602 --> 01:06:15,036
Well, so in light of your test,

1011
01:06:15,038 --> 01:06:17,539
if those athlete's
lives depended

1012
01:06:17,541 --> 01:06:19,541
on jumping those 12 feet,

1013
01:06:19,543 --> 01:06:22,110
how many
would still be alive today?

1014
01:06:22,112 --> 01:06:24,679
None of them.

1015
01:06:24,681 --> 01:06:26,721
I mean, unless they had wings,
you know.

1016
01:06:30,454 --> 01:06:32,654
Thank you.

1017
01:06:32,656 --> 01:06:33,722
I'm a medical doctor,

1018
01:06:33,724 --> 01:06:35,557
specializing
in forensic pathology.

1019
01:06:35,559 --> 01:06:37,726
I've taught the subject
for the past 12 years

1020
01:06:37,728 --> 01:06:39,561
at the Wisconsin State
Medical School,

1021
01:06:39,563 --> 01:06:42,197
and was a coroner
for over 20 years.

1022
01:06:42,199 --> 01:06:45,767
No, Kevin Thacker's autopsy
was done by the county coroner.

1023
01:06:45,769 --> 01:06:49,738
Mr. Thacker died from a
contrecoup injury to the brain.

1024
01:06:49,740 --> 01:06:52,540
The two types of injuries
are a coup and contrecoup.

1025
01:06:52,542 --> 01:06:55,777
Since the brain floats
in the fluid of the skull,

1026
01:06:55,779 --> 01:06:57,612
and is subject to movement,

1027
01:06:57,614 --> 01:07:00,615
in a coup injury,
the skull would hit an object,

1028
01:07:00,617 --> 01:07:04,052
such as a fall, and the brain
hits the side of the skull

1029
01:07:04,054 --> 01:07:05,487
where the impact occurred.

1030
01:07:05,489 --> 01:07:09,024
In Kevin's injury,
an object hit the skull,

1031
01:07:09,026 --> 01:07:13,361
not the reverse,
producing a contrecoup injury.

1032
01:07:13,363 --> 01:07:16,364
This forces the brain to
the other side of the skull.

1033
01:07:16,366 --> 01:07:20,201
In his case: Blunt object
hitting the left temporal bone

1034
01:07:20,203 --> 01:07:23,471
causing bleeding
in the right temporal lobe.

1035
01:07:23,473 --> 01:07:26,241
Doctor, did the autopsy report

1036
01:07:26,243 --> 01:07:31,079
reveal any other injuries
to Kevin, at all?

1037
01:07:31,081 --> 01:07:33,381
There was bruises
underneath his armpits,

1038
01:07:33,383 --> 01:07:36,501
but other than that, no.

1039
01:07:36,502 --> 01:07:39,620
The defense claims that Kevin
died from a fall of 24 feet

1040
01:07:39,623 --> 01:07:42,290
onto an asphalt surface.

1041
01:07:42,292 --> 01:07:44,092
Well, bluntly put,

1042
01:07:44,094 --> 01:07:47,762
that would defy both
medical and biological science.

1043
01:07:47,764 --> 01:07:49,497
It's outrageous, really.

1044
01:07:49,499 --> 01:07:52,667
He would have multiple bruising
where the impact occurred,

1045
01:07:52,669 --> 01:07:55,370
other bone fractures,
damages to his organs,

1046
01:07:55,372 --> 01:07:58,807
which Mr. Thacker did not have.

1047
01:07:58,809 --> 01:08:01,076
Thank you, Doctor.

1048
01:08:11,621 --> 01:08:15,123
Dr. Booker, how long have you
been a state medical examiner

1049
01:08:15,125 --> 01:08:17,759
and what does that job entail?

1050
01:08:17,761 --> 01:08:19,327
Well, I specialize

1051
01:08:19,329 --> 01:08:21,262
in comprehensive
medical examinations,

1052
01:08:21,264 --> 01:08:23,098
primarily postmortem.

1053
01:08:23,100 --> 01:08:24,599
And for five years,
I've worked as an expert witness

1054
01:08:24,601 --> 01:08:26,434
for the police department.

1055
01:08:26,436 --> 01:08:30,238
And in your expert opinion,
from what height can a person

1056
01:08:30,240 --> 01:08:34,142
hit the ground
without sustaining injury?

1057
01:08:34,144 --> 01:08:36,611
A body can fall
from as high as six stories

1058
01:08:36,613 --> 01:08:38,546
without sustaining injury.

1059
01:08:39,749 --> 01:08:41,749
Six stories. Thank you.

1060
01:08:41,751 --> 01:08:44,586
No further questions,
Your Honor.

1061
01:08:44,588 --> 01:08:46,654
Cross examine, Mr. Pepper.

1062
01:08:53,897 --> 01:08:58,299
Um, let me get this straight.

1063
01:08:58,301 --> 01:09:00,168
Now, you just testified

1064
01:09:00,170 --> 01:09:03,805
that a body can fall
six stories

1065
01:09:03,807 --> 01:09:06,241
without sustaining an injury.

1066
01:09:06,243 --> 01:09:07,775
Is that correct?

1067
01:09:07,777 --> 01:09:09,377
Yes, yes.

1068
01:09:09,379 --> 01:09:11,246
If there's an equal,
instantaneous transference

1069
01:09:11,248 --> 01:09:14,616
between the body
and the ground.

1070
01:09:14,618 --> 01:09:15,898
Right.

1071
01:09:17,354 --> 01:09:20,555
Well, now what is that?

1072
01:09:20,557 --> 01:09:24,392
Can you demonstrate
that for us right now?

1073
01:09:24,394 --> 01:09:26,461
Let's just say, three feet.

1074
01:09:26,463 --> 01:09:30,231
And you choose
which side you land on.

1075
01:09:30,233 --> 01:09:31,499
No.

1076
01:09:31,501 --> 01:09:34,869
Why? Are you afraid
of getting hurt?

1077
01:09:37,374 --> 01:09:40,942
Okay, lets say two feet.

1078
01:09:40,944 --> 01:09:41,943
One foot?

1079
01:09:41,945 --> 01:09:44,179
Objection. Your Honor,

1080
01:09:44,181 --> 01:09:45,647
if Mr. Pepper
wants someone to fall,

1081
01:09:45,649 --> 01:09:47,715
let him demonstrate it himself.

1082
01:09:47,717 --> 01:09:49,584
Sustained. Mr. Pepper.

1083
01:10:01,631 --> 01:10:03,432
Can you tell me what this is?

1084
01:10:03,967 --> 01:10:05,500
That's a physics equation.

1085
01:10:05,502 --> 01:10:10,371
Force equals mass
times acceleration.

1086
01:10:10,373 --> 01:10:12,941
Now, based on this equation,

1087
01:10:12,943 --> 01:10:15,510
can you tell me at what force.

1088
01:10:15,512 --> 01:10:17,912
Kevin's body
hit the ground with?

1089
01:10:19,516 --> 01:10:21,883
No. No, I can't.

1090
01:10:21,885 --> 01:10:23,551
Why not?

1091
01:10:23,553 --> 01:10:25,820
Look,
I'm a medical examiner, okay?

1092
01:10:25,822 --> 01:10:27,989
I'm not good at math.

1093
01:10:31,461 --> 01:10:33,494
No further questions,
Your Honor.

1094
01:10:41,371 --> 01:10:44,105
<i>The court room</i>

1095
01:10:44,106 --> 01:10:46,840
<i>is one of the most</i>
<i>unpredictable places on earth.</i>

1096
01:10:46,843 --> 01:10:50,612
<i>You never know</i>
<i>exactly what you're up against.</i>

1097
01:10:50,614 --> 01:10:54,249
<i>You just hope</i>
<i>you can inspire that jury.</i>

1098
01:10:55,385 --> 01:10:57,552
I've known Officer Dodge
for six years;

1099
01:10:57,554 --> 01:10:59,254
Detective Pebble for ten.

1100
01:10:59,256 --> 01:11:00,888
How would you describe
Officer Dodge?

1101
01:11:00,890 --> 01:11:04,525
Well, he's a big young man,
but he's certainly not a bully.

1102
01:11:04,527 --> 01:11:07,028
He's just an officer
that comes to work every day,

1103
01:11:07,030 --> 01:11:08,930
and goes about
his business quietly.

1104
01:11:08,932 --> 01:11:10,565
And Detective Pebble?

1105
01:11:10,567 --> 01:11:11,866
Oh, Detective Pebble is simply

1106
01:11:11,868 --> 01:11:13,401
the best cop
I've ever worked with.

1107
01:11:13,403 --> 01:11:17,005
Chief Wilson, have
you ever known Officer Dodge

1108
01:11:17,007 --> 01:11:19,540
to have a problem
with his temper?

1109
01:11:19,542 --> 01:11:22,343
The young man had some
difficulties in Vietnam,

1110
01:11:22,345 --> 01:11:23,645
but since I've known him,

1111
01:11:23,647 --> 01:11:25,880
he's made hundreds of arrests
without incident,

1112
01:11:25,882 --> 01:11:28,616
all of them good.

1113
01:11:28,617 --> 01:11:31,351
Chief, would you please
tell this court your opinion

1114
01:11:31,354 --> 01:11:35,723
on the theory that Kevin
Thacker's death was a cover-up.

1115
01:11:35,725 --> 01:11:39,494
No, no. Not in my department.

1116
01:11:39,496 --> 01:11:41,329
Simply there wasn't
enough time.

1117
01:11:41,331 --> 01:11:44,932
I mean, you take this arbitrary
video tape of the ordeal,

1118
01:11:44,934 --> 01:11:47,235
one to seven minutes.

1119
01:11:47,236 --> 01:11:49,537
There's not enough time
in there to concoct a cover-up.

1120
01:11:49,539 --> 01:11:51,005
Thank you, Chief Wilson.

1121
01:11:51,007 --> 01:11:53,308
No further questions
at this time, Your Honor.

1122
01:11:53,310 --> 01:11:55,677
Mr. Pepper?

1123
01:11:55,679 --> 01:12:00,481
Well, actually,
the time frame is quite clear.

1124
01:12:00,483 --> 01:12:01,883
Dodge sounded the alarm

1125
01:12:01,885 --> 01:12:05,620
at 1:17 a.m.,

1126
01:12:05,622 --> 01:12:07,922
that's from your station logs,

1127
01:12:07,924 --> 01:12:10,792
and Dodge discovered
the body at 1:24 a.m.

1128
01:12:10,794 --> 01:12:13,594
That's seven minutes.

1129
01:12:14,898 --> 01:12:17,432
Should we allow the court to
have seven minutes of silence

1130
01:12:17,434 --> 01:12:21,436
right now, just to understand
how long that actually is?

1131
01:12:43,460 --> 01:12:45,393
That's not even
30 seconds, Chief.

1132
01:12:48,031 --> 01:12:52,567
Do you really think that
this couldn't have occurred?

1133
01:12:52,569 --> 01:12:56,070
Not on my watch;
Not in my department.

1134
01:13:02,712 --> 01:13:07,615
Detective Pebble, how long have
you known Officer John Dodge?

1135
01:13:08,852 --> 01:13:10,918
Ten years.

1136
01:13:10,920 --> 01:13:13,621
And just to be clear
for the court,

1137
01:13:13,623 --> 01:13:16,891
it was you who investigated
the death of Kevin Thacker?

1138
01:13:16,893 --> 01:13:19,694
Yes, I did.

1139
01:13:19,696 --> 01:13:22,797
Did you investigate whether
John Dodge committed a crime

1140
01:13:22,799 --> 01:13:26,534
on the night
of October 29th, 1983?

1141
01:13:26,536 --> 01:13:29,670
No.

1142
01:13:29,672 --> 01:13:33,007
Well, why not?

1143
01:13:33,009 --> 01:13:35,943
No crime was committed,
except by Kevin Thacker.

1144
01:13:35,945 --> 01:13:40,047
You never,
not even for a moment,

1145
01:13:40,049 --> 01:13:44,152
considered the culpability
of Officer Dodge?

1146
01:13:45,989 --> 01:13:47,822
There's no evidence
to support that.

1147
01:13:47,824 --> 01:13:50,625
Where were you
during the booking?

1148
01:13:51,961 --> 01:13:54,962
Somebody was getting beat up
across the street,

1149
01:13:54,964 --> 01:13:56,597
I was on a radio call for that.

1150
01:13:56,599 --> 01:14:00,668
But, I returned shortly after
the ambulance was called.

1151
01:14:00,670 --> 01:14:02,136
And, where was Officer Dodge?

1152
01:14:02,138 --> 01:14:04,906
He was with the victim.

1153
01:14:04,908 --> 01:14:07,575
Who notified Kevin's parents?

1154
01:14:07,577 --> 01:14:08,976
The Des Moines PD.

1155
01:14:08,978 --> 01:14:12,046
Why didn't you do
the notification?

1156
01:14:12,048 --> 01:14:14,882
Because I was busy collecting
evidence and statements

1157
01:14:14,884 --> 01:14:18,119
with respect to Mr. Thacker's
unfortunate fall.

1158
01:14:18,121 --> 01:14:20,721
Really? Well, what
did that consist of?

1159
01:14:20,723 --> 01:14:24,826
Talking to the parties involved;
Interviewing them.

1160
01:14:24,828 --> 01:14:27,061
That's when I found out
about Kevin's mental state

1161
01:14:27,063 --> 01:14:29,230
during the arrest.

1162
01:14:29,232 --> 01:14:32,633
Turns out
the boy was broken-hearted.

1163
01:14:32,635 --> 01:14:35,937
How could you possibly be aware
of Kevin's mental state?

1164
01:14:35,939 --> 01:14:37,555
Because I interviewed
his boyfriend.

1165
01:14:37,556 --> 01:14:39,172
His boyfriend said he had
showed up at Marshalltown...

1166
01:14:39,175 --> 01:14:42,243
Detective,
Kevin's sexual orientation

1167
01:14:42,245 --> 01:14:43,945
is not on trial here,

1168
01:14:43,947 --> 01:14:46,881
your colleague John Dodge is.

1169
01:14:46,883 --> 01:14:48,616
Look, I'm not going
to allow you

1170
01:14:48,618 --> 01:14:50,318
to dance around this
any longer.

1171
01:14:50,319 --> 01:14:52,019
I want you to tell the court,
beat by beat,

1172
01:14:52,021 --> 01:14:54,489
moment by moment,
what happened?

1173
01:14:56,159 --> 01:14:58,693
Prisoner is loose
in the building.

1174
01:15:27,924 --> 01:15:32,226
So he did all this,
while intoxicated,

1175
01:15:32,228 --> 01:15:34,095
leaping like
a world-class athlete,

1176
01:15:34,097 --> 01:15:35,696
dropping the cigarette
and lighter,

1177
01:15:35,698 --> 01:15:40,067
and falling 24 feet,
only sustaining one injury.

1178
01:15:40,069 --> 01:15:41,869
Yes, it appears that way, yes.

1179
01:15:41,871 --> 01:15:44,572
After Kevin was taken
to the hospital,

1180
01:15:44,574 --> 01:15:47,041
why did have his clothes
ordered back to the station?

1181
01:15:47,043 --> 01:15:49,110
To be used as evidence.
I already told you that.

1182
01:15:49,112 --> 01:15:52,713
And to allow you to fabricate
your version of the events.

1183
01:15:52,715 --> 01:15:54,615
You had time
to plant the cigarette,

1184
01:15:54,617 --> 01:15:58,553
and create the evidence, because
it didn't matter, detective.

1185
01:15:58,555 --> 01:16:02,256
Kevin Thacker
was never on that roof.

1186
01:16:07,130 --> 01:16:09,010
No further questions,
Your Honor.

1187
01:16:17,807 --> 01:16:20,308
Thank you
for being here, Mrs. Thacker.

1188
01:16:20,310 --> 01:16:22,910
I don't think anyone
in this room would argue

1189
01:16:22,912 --> 01:16:25,279
that this is a very tough thing
for you to do.

1190
01:16:25,281 --> 01:16:29,050
It hasn't been easy.

1191
01:16:29,052 --> 01:16:31,953
Will you please tell the court

1192
01:16:31,955 --> 01:16:35,356
a little bit about Kevin?

1193
01:16:35,358 --> 01:16:36,924
What he was like.

1194
01:16:36,926 --> 01:16:38,225
Sure.

1195
01:16:38,227 --> 01:16:42,163
Kevin was a good son.

1196
01:16:42,165 --> 01:16:44,799
Very good son. Funny, smart.

1197
01:16:44,801 --> 01:16:49,236
He was going
to community college.

1198
01:16:49,238 --> 01:16:52,039
Did...?

1199
01:16:52,041 --> 01:16:54,875
Did Kevin have
a drinking problem?

1200
01:16:55,878 --> 01:16:59,614
I think he was just young,
acting his age.

1201
01:16:59,616 --> 01:17:03,217
Maybe a little lost at times.

1202
01:17:05,922 --> 01:17:09,290
You know, he may have had
some issues with alcohol,

1203
01:17:09,292 --> 01:17:12,927
but I think more
he just never knew exactly

1204
01:17:12,929 --> 01:17:16,330
where to direct his attention.

1205
01:17:16,332 --> 01:17:21,002
And what will you miss most

1206
01:17:21,004 --> 01:17:22,269
about Kevin?

1207
01:17:22,271 --> 01:17:24,705
Objection, Your Honor.
Relevance.

1208
01:17:24,707 --> 01:17:27,675
Trying to make
the deceased a person,

1209
01:17:27,677 --> 01:17:29,910
not just a name, Your Honor.

1210
01:17:29,912 --> 01:17:31,345
Overruled.

1211
01:17:31,347 --> 01:17:33,414
You can answer, Ma'am.

1212
01:17:38,221 --> 01:17:42,823
I'll miss sitting at the table
with him, after dinner,

1213
01:17:42,825 --> 01:17:46,260
just the two of us, talking.

1214
01:17:46,262 --> 01:17:49,997
I used to give him the business
about putting on his shirt,

1215
01:17:49,999 --> 01:17:53,000
and he'd never listen to me.

1216
01:17:53,002 --> 01:17:56,337
He'd just say,
"We're done eatin', Ma. Relax."

1217
01:17:58,408 --> 01:18:02,743
Believe it or not,
I'll miss worrying about him.

1218
01:18:02,745 --> 01:18:05,012
It's just,
after you give birth,

1219
01:18:05,014 --> 01:18:07,181
it becomes ingrained in you.

1220
01:18:07,183 --> 01:18:10,451
It's just like a part of you,
as long as you live.

1221
01:18:10,453 --> 01:18:13,287
That worry
is just always there.

1222
01:18:13,289 --> 01:18:15,222
I'll miss that.

1223
01:18:16,392 --> 01:18:18,059
And, what else will you miss?

1224
01:18:21,698 --> 01:18:24,131
Everything.

1225
01:18:24,133 --> 01:18:27,068
Everything that would've
come after.

1226
01:18:38,147 --> 01:18:40,281
Sorry.

1227
01:18:40,283 --> 01:18:42,883
Thank you, Beverly.

1228
01:18:54,130 --> 01:18:56,030
Hey, guys.

1229
01:18:56,032 --> 01:18:58,552
Hey, Mike. How are you?

1230
01:18:59,068 --> 01:19:02,269
Stu?

1231
01:19:02,271 --> 01:19:04,472
I want to tell you
how much I appreciate

1232
01:19:04,474 --> 01:19:08,409
your work on this case.

1233
01:19:08,411 --> 01:19:12,346
And I wish
Kevin could have met you.

1234
01:19:15,017 --> 01:19:16,350
Thank you.

1235
01:19:16,352 --> 01:19:18,085
Thanks.

1236
01:19:33,236 --> 01:19:37,138
You have
a difficult task today,

1237
01:19:37,140 --> 01:19:41,275
and I'd like to start off
by thanking you

1238
01:19:41,277 --> 01:19:44,278
for your time and attention

1239
01:19:44,280 --> 01:19:47,114
in this crucial case.

1240
01:19:49,285 --> 01:19:52,219
Your task today is difficult

1241
01:19:52,221 --> 01:19:55,022
because I'm asking you
to believe

1242
01:19:55,024 --> 01:19:59,260
that the people
you have been taught to trust

1243
01:19:59,262 --> 01:20:04,098
are the same people responsible
for the death of Kevin Thacker.

1244
01:20:05,301 --> 01:20:08,502
Now, if you asked me
a year ago,

1245
01:20:08,504 --> 01:20:11,305
if I believed something
like this could be be possible,

1246
01:20:11,307 --> 01:20:15,075
I'd have had a hard time
believing it too.

1247
01:20:16,412 --> 01:20:20,414
But I'm learning.

1248
01:20:20,416 --> 01:20:24,051
I'm learning that, inherently,
we were put on this Earth

1249
01:20:24,053 --> 01:20:27,154
to protect one another.

1250
01:20:30,092 --> 01:20:32,293
There's an old saying:

1251
01:20:32,295 --> 01:20:36,330
"Absolute power
corrupts absolutely."

1252
01:20:36,332 --> 01:20:38,365
We've all heard that statement.

1253
01:20:38,367 --> 01:20:41,068
And it trickles all the way down
the power chain,

1254
01:20:41,070 --> 01:20:44,038
from a president
to a meter maid.

1255
01:20:44,040 --> 01:20:47,174
To make those who think
they're above the law

1256
01:20:47,176 --> 01:20:50,911
be fearful of its consequences.

1257
01:20:50,913 --> 01:20:55,015
Checks and balances.

1258
01:20:55,017 --> 01:20:57,418
That sounds like
a pretty good idea to me.

1259
01:20:57,420 --> 01:21:00,988
What do you think?
I mean, there's history here.

1260
01:21:00,990 --> 01:21:03,057
Going back to the Middle Ages,

1261
01:21:03,059 --> 01:21:07,061
the Spanish Inquisition,
police states,

1262
01:21:07,063 --> 01:21:10,231
and the creation of laws.

1263
01:21:10,233 --> 01:21:11,432
New laws had to be passed

1264
01:21:11,434 --> 01:21:15,236
to keep the abuse of power
in check.

1265
01:21:15,238 --> 01:21:19,540
The Fourth Amendment protects us
from search and seizure,

1266
01:21:19,542 --> 01:21:23,444
and the Fourteenth Amendment
gives us our rights.

1267
01:21:23,446 --> 01:21:28,048
I never knew Kevin Thacker.

